This audio segment was recorded on 29 June 2025 as part of a Passive Acoustic Monitoring (PAM) test carried out in Medes Island using a HydroMoth device (AudioMoth Firmware Basic v1.11.0) at a depth of 5 meters. 
This audio is part of a longer recording (~10 minutes) and features some tonal vocalisations produced by a dolphin in the waters surrounding Medes Islands.
Based on the geographic location and the acoustic characteristics of the signals—particularly the presence of whistles with frequencies ranging from 5 kHz to 14 kHz—it is most likely that these vocalizations were produced by bottlenose dolphins.
The recording was made at 09:36:10 UTC by device AudioMoth 2474750763FB80C5, using a 250 kHz sampling rate and low-to-medium gain settings. At the time of recording, the battery voltage was 3.5 V and the temperature was 24.8°C. A high-pass filter at 3.5 kHz was applied to attenuate low-frequency background noise and enhance signal clarity.
The sonogram image accompanying the audio file was generated using Raven Lite: Interactive Sound Analysis Software (Version 2.0.5), developed by K. Lisa Yang. Center for Conservation Bioacoustics at the Cornell Lab of Ornithology (2024).
